{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:22:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:22:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18142"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73633"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10856"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59106"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25259"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73633"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe median nerve is an important structure in the hand, providing both motor and sensory innervation to specific regions. Its anatomical position relative to other structures is crucial for understanding its function and potential sites of compression or injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of the median nerve within the hand?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS) tendons","Lateral to the flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendons","Lateral to the flexor pollicis longus (FPL) tendon","Medial to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS) tendons","Medial to the flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendons"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe median nerve is located \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS) tendons\u003C/strong\u003E in the hand. This positioning is important for its role in innervating the thenar muscles and providing sensation to the lateral aspect of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral to the flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendons\u003C/strong\u003E - The FDP tendons are deeper and more medial compared to the median nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral to the flexor pollicis longus (FPL) tendon\u003C/strong\u003E - The FPL tendon is located more laterally and anteriorly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS) tendons\u003C/strong\u003E - The median nerve is lateral, not medial, to the FDS tendons\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial to the flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendons\u003C/strong\u003E - The median nerve is not medial to the FDP tendons\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomical position of the median nerve is essential for diagnosing conditions such as carpal tunnel syndrome, where the nerve can become compressed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The median nerve in the hand is located lateral to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS) tendons.","The median nerve provides motor innervation to the thenar muscles and lateral two lumbricals.","The median nerve provides sensory innervation to the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, middle, and lateral half of the ring finger."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences250"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59106"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59106"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T00:57:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T00:58:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10856"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73633"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{